   "id": "3f5c4fab",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Reinforcement Learning In PyWorld3-03 With Some Control Functions\n",
    "\n",
    "**Authors of this modified file:** Evelina Örsvik and Linnea Stålberg\n",
    "\n",
    "**Date of modifications:** March-April 2026\n",
    "\n",
    "**Note on original authors:** This file is an adaptation of Emil Johansson and Linnéa Bäckvall's reinforcement learning file `reinforcementLearning.ipynb` available at https://github.com/emilj610/pyworld3A3. It has been modified to fit our (the authors') purposes.\n",
    "\n",
    "*We have also referred to lecture notes in the KTH course DD1420 as well as documentation of relevant libraries, [PyTorch beginner tutorials](https://docs.pytorch.org/tutorials/beginner/basics/intro.html), World3 literature and the bachelor thesis report of Emil Johansson and Linnéa Bäckvall.*\n",
    "\n",
    "The goal is to train a neural network to approximate a cumulative reward function $J$ with the approximation $\\hat J$. Then we try to find better controls than used for the standard run (using $\\hat J$ as the objective function to optimise) by doing a grid search.\n",
    "\n",
    "Running this file successfully requires having training data first. Training data can be obtained by running `data_generation.py`.\n",
    "\n",
    "The disposition of the file is the following:\n",
    "\n",
    "1.  Initial setup\n",
    "2.  Data extraction and training of neural network\n",
    "3.  Optimization\n",
    "4.  Plot results"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "74334f14",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Initial setup"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a6d7fad3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Import libraries, define some constants, initialise a standard run of World3-03, and define reward function(s)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 279,
   "id": "78b999c0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Imports\n",
    "\n",
    "# General, used throughout the file\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from pyworld3 import World3\n",
    "from matplotlib import pyplot as plt\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "from tqdm import tqdm # used for progress bar\n",
    "\n",
    "# For nn training\n",
    "import torch\n",
    "import torch.nn as nn\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
    "\n",
    "# To save data between runs\n",
    "import json\n",
    "import os\n",
    "import pickle # to save StandardScalers # https://stackoverflow.com/questions/10592605/save-classifier-to-disk-in-scikit-learn, https://scikit-learn.org/stable/model_persistence.html, https://docs.python.org/3/library/pickle.html\n",
    "\n",
    "# Specials\n",
    "from pyworld3.utils import plot_world_variables, standard_setup\n",
    "from rewards import *\n",
    "from control_maps_and_loops import *"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 280,
   "id": "12ca8e79",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Define constants to be used throughout the file\n",
    "MIN_YEAR = 1900\n",
    "MAX_YEAR = 2100\n",
    "FAST = True # select, for runs where it is safe, whether to run with fast=True or fast=False; fast=False is always used for some runs\n",
    "NOISE = True\n",
    "\n",
    "# Used to load existing NN model if wished\n",
    "# This NN model will replace the one trained in this file unless LOAD_NN_TRAIN_ID = None or LOAD_NN_RL_ID = None\n",
    "# If NN model is loaded it is not saved anew (unless SAVE_RESULTS=False). Let LOAD_NN_TRAIN_ID = None or LOAD_NN_RL_ID = None to save the model that is trained.\n",
    "LOAD_NN_TRAIN_ID = None # train ID of NN model to load, set to None if you do not wish to load existing NN model\n",
    "LOAD_NN_RL_ID = \"12\" # RL ID of NN model to load, set to None if you do not wish to load existing NN model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 281,
   "id": "a7e59419",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Standard run until MAX_YEAR\n",
    "world_reference = World3(year_min=MIN_YEAR, year_max=MAX_YEAR, noise=NOISE)\n",
    "standard_setup(world_reference)\n",
    "world_reference.run_world3(fast=False) # use fast=False here for extra safety\n",
    "\n",
    "STD_SEED = world_reference.seed"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ef7323ed",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here we define the Human Welfare Index (built into World3-03) as the reward function, $g$. Most likely we will also define other reward functions in the future."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 282,
   "id": "b774d340",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def reward_HSDI(world, k=None):\n",
    "    return reward_HSDI_ref(world, world_reference, k)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fe5d3fe3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data extraction and training of neural network"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "046f4776",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this section we extract the data from its storage, preprocess it, and use it to train a neural network. We also plot the loss. The disposition of this section is as follows:\n",
    "\n",
    "1.  Data extraction and setup\n",
    "2.  Preprocessing\n",
    "3.  Training and creating a function\n",
    "4.  Loss comparison"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ca576efc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Data extraction and setup"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dba02558",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Running this requires a file with training data. Training data should include cumulative rewards $J$ (throughout each run) and state variables (throughout each run) stored for runs with randomised initial values."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 283,
   "id": "1ae626b8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "reward_dict = {\"HSDI\" : reward_HSDI,\n",
    "               \"HWI\" : reward_hwi,\n",
    "               \"doughnut\" : reward_doughnut}\n",
    "\n",
    "reward_name = \"doughnut\"\n",
    "reward_func = reward_dict[reward_name]\n",
    "\n",
    "IN_ID = \"11\"  # data from data generation\n",
    "\n",
    "reward_func_name = reward_func.__name__\n",
    "filepath = f\"datasets/traintest/{reward_name}/{IN_ID}_data_{reward_name}.parquet\"\n",
    "\n",
    "df = pd.read_parquet(filepath)\n",
    "STATE_VARIABLES = df.columns[df.columns != \"J\"]\n",
    "no_init_vars = [\"time\"] # specify which variables are not \"initialable\""
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "808c1f16",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Define a neural network class (requires imports from PyTorch and scikit-learn, imported in the beginning of this file). Use two hidden layers and ReLU activation ($\\text{act}(z)=\\max(0, z)$) throughout the forward pass. Note that `nn.Module` is a base class that our class `neuralNet` builds upon."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 284,
   "id": "fe7c10c3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class neuralNet(nn.Module):\n",
    "    def __init__(self, in_dim, out_dim):\n",
    "        # 2 hidden layers\n",
    "        super(neuralNet, self).__init__()\n",
    "        self.input_layer = nn.Linear(in_features=in_dim, out_features=32)\n",
    "        self.hidden_layer1 = nn.Linear(in_features=32, out_features=64)\n",
    "        self.hidden_layer2 = nn.Linear(in_features=64, out_features=32)\n",
    "        self.outLayer = nn.Linear(in_features=32, out_features=out_dim)\n",
    "\n",
    "    def forward(self, x):\n",
    "        # forward pass with relu activation function\n",
    "        x = self.input_layer(x)\n",
    "        x = torch.relu(self.hidden_layer1(x))\n",
    "        x = torch.relu(self.hidden_layer2(x))\n",
    "        x = self.outLayer(x)\n",
    "        return x"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "06346fdf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Preprocessing"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3caa4e0b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here we preprocess the data before feeding it to our neural network.\n",
    "\n",
    "We split the data so that 80% is used for training and 20% for testing. One can change these proportions by modifying `test_size` in `train_test_split` call. Selecting `random_state=42` allows us to reproduce results across multiple function calls. For further information see the documentation of `sklearn.model_selection.train_test_split`.\n",
    "\n",
    "We also normalise the data to increase stability and speed of the neural network.\n",
    "For $X$ (i.e., state variables) and $J$ (i.e., true reward) separately, we fit a `StandardScaler` to the training data, then transform the data using the mean and standard deviation obtained during fitting. Then we also transform the training data with the same mean and standard deviation (separately for $X$ and $J$).\n",
    "\n",
    "After normalising the data, we turn it into PyTorch tensors (similar to ndarrays in NumPy)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 285,
   "id": "8a1a5209",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "X = df.drop(columns=[\"J\"]).to_numpy()\n",
    "J = df[\"J\"].to_numpy().reshape(-1,1)\n",
    "\n",
    "X_train, X_test, J_train, J_test = train_test_split(X, J, test_size=0.2, random_state=42) # change test_size for different proportion of training/testing data\n",
    "\n",
    "# normalising\n",
    "X_normaliser = StandardScaler()\n",
    "X_train = X_normaliser.fit_transform(X_train)\n",
    "X_test = X_normaliser.transform(X_test)\n",
    "J_normaliser = StandardScaler()\n",
    "J_train = J_normaliser.fit_transform(J_train)\n",
    "J_test = J_normaliser.transform(J_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "# turning into pytorch tensors\n",
    "X_train = torch.tensor(X_train, dtype=torch.float32)\n",
    "X_test = torch.tensor(X_test, dtype=torch.float32)\n",
    "J_train = torch.tensor(J_train, dtype=torch.float32)\n",
    "J_test = torch.tensor(J_test, dtype=torch.float32)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9f770b3e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now `X_train` is a PyTorch tensor with each datapoint stored as a row. So the dimension of one datapoint is `X_train.shape[1]` (number of columns in `X_train`)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c49d31bb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Training and creating a function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "886e4fcc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here we create a neural network model using mean squared error (MSE) loss. As an optimiser we use Adam (Adaptive Moment Estimation) built into PyTorch. Further, we use the learning rate 0.001. For details please see the `torch.optim.Adam` documentation and PyTorch tutorials, in particular https://docs.pytorch.org/tutorials/beginner/basics/optimization_tutorial.html. We train the NN using the runs (without control functions) with randomised initial state variables (randomised with Gaussian distribution around standard run initial values) that our training data set consists of. The NN is trained to represent the approximative cumulative reward, $\\hat J$."
   ]
  },
